Text: As the project nears completion, I can't help thinking about how our client, especially Kuku, will manage the hand-over.
To be fair, at this point we have implemented the basic functionalities required.
From Eric's perspective, there's a map that allows users to search for mines.
There's a database that stores all the information.
There's a pipeline that processes the varied data.
He probably wouldn't have much to say about how everything is written, organized, and deployed.
From Kuku's perspective, we have definitely deviated from the initial specs.
The pipeline uses Python, the database MongoDB.
Oh well, at least the UI still makes use of PHP and MySQL.
I don't really know how he would make of it, but when I let him know of our adjustments on Wednesday, his only response was "interesting".
Of course, it was in the middle of a meet-up, so I doubt that Kuku really meant anything serious then and there.
But for some reason I couldn't stop musing about this incidence.
It was the same feeling I experienced when I proposed to my team that we should use MongoDB instead.
Even now, I'm not even sure that I've made the right decision.
Technically speaking, I may haven't done enough research to justify the switch.
In terms of the effect it has on my team members, I think it hasn't altered people's roles and responsibilities too much, given that I pictured the API as separated from the UI and pipeline.
I don't know.
Maybe I'm only blindly following the principle of "separation of concerns" at other people's expenses.
Or maybe the switch did simply things for my team members.
I can't really tell.
Guess one goal for next week's meeting is to just ask them about it.
Against this background, I'm having some uncertainties about my choice of a report.
I want it to be technical, but also want it to be slightly reflective/critical so as to explain my choices of technologies.
So I guess some parts of it would go beyond walk-through instructions and look at the overall organization.
I'd also like to explain how the way our team's components are arranged and written make the codes modular, maintainable and expandable.
A bird's-eye view, so to say.
As such, I would really appreciate your help in giving all these ideas a common label so that I could enforce some structure on them.
Another related thing that concerns me is who the target audience is.
I feel like there are at least two here:  a developer who needs to learn how to use the system, and a more critical observer who is interested in some technical analysis.
Perhaps I should just pick one over the other, but I don't really know whether things are as clear-cut.
To end this week's reflection, I think it's really hard to answer the title's question.
If you were paid to implement rather than to lead or to choose, perhaps things would've been more black and white.

I know that the project is a chance for each person to explore new areas or deepen their understanding, but I think the reality is it also shows how hard it is to keep the balance among the various stakeholders of the project.
Regardless of what Kuku and Eric make of our project, I really hope that my teammates haven't been affected too much.
Oh well, let's see how it goes comes Monday's meeting.
Overall
